    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-08-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-08-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="364"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d364">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.801/639</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Chief of the Division of Trade
                        Agreements</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Deimel</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-16">August 16,
                            1935</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A revised ship subsidy measure has been introduced into the Senate by Senator
                    Copeland, “by request” (S. 3376, July 29, calendar day, August 6, 1935<note
                        n="19" xml:id="d364fn19">
                        <hi rend="italic">Congressional Record</hi>, vol. 79, pt. 12, p.
                        12534.</note>) in place of the bill which he withdrew following the passage
                    of Congressman Bland’s Bill by the House.<note n="20" xml:id="d364fn20">The
                        Bland Bill, H. R. 8555, known as the Merchant Marine Act of 1936, was passed
                        by Congress and approved June 29, 1936; 49 Stat. 1985.</note>
                </p>
                <p>This new bill differs in a number of important points not only from Senator
                    Copeland’s earlier bill, but also from the Bland Bill. It provides for subsidies
                        (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) for ship building to meet the difference between
                    foreign and domestic construction costs, and (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) for
                    operation <pb facs="0582" n="480" xml:id="pg_480"/> to meet the difference
                    between foreign and domestic operating costs, but contains no provision for the
                    third, “trade penetration” or “fighting ships” subsidy. Likewise, the earlier
                    proposals to give specific authorization to the maritime authority for the
                    fixing of rates in foreign commerce are omitted.</p>
                <p>Accordingly, aside from the inclusion in the declaration of policies that the
                    United States should have: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“… a merchant marine sufficient to carry its domestic water borne
                            commerce and at least one-half of the water borne export and import
                            foreign commerce of the United States,”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">The principal features in the earlier subsidy bills to which the
                    Department might have serious objections have been eliminated from this
                    bill.</p>
            </div>
